<p>
    In the united states, when this paper was written in 2021, The united states had around one quarter of all data center servers globally, with those data centers taking about 1.8% of all Energy that was used in the country. It doesn't sound too bad, but that is just raw energy from the grid, that does not take into account the generators on site, or the private energy farms that are popping up. Water is also another consideration that was discussed heavily, with it also being a resource that is used very heavily by data centers. In this paper it shows, not only the basins where this is happening, but each subbasin in the entire country to give a good referenece on the differences. This paper is significantly different as it shows the real world environmental impact of data centers, not just the engery, but even the man power it took to produce the raw metals that are needed. 
</p>


<p id="topicSixMore" style="display: none;">
    In a reference to a previous topic that was discussed, (The Lithium miners that were stalked by the Federal Government) The author of the paper, <i>Kate Crawford</i>, actually drove to Nevada and attended one of the only functioning lithium mines in the United states at the time. to not go too into depth on the paper, she mentions specifically the diference in wealth. That stuck with me, where she described the wealth despair compared to San Francisco, even though most of all the precious metal of Lithium came from there in the United states at the time. Where she says that the people are never gaining, only bearing the cost of all the enviornmental impacts. 

    Crawford links a colonial mindset of thinking that causes this phenomemon to happen constantly. She specifically mentions the striking similarities of mines being forced onto indigenous land, then those same indigenous community members are forced to work there, as it becomes the only source of employment in the area. That showing a similarity to everything we have been learning in this class. It is the same ideology that happens over time in history again and again, where AI was propped as a change in humanity for the better, it turns out to be the same humanity in where the indigenous communities that inhabit the areas surrounding the data centers. 

    The end result seems to be a mass push towards artifical intelligence by all the governments that can afford it, as it takes a extraordinary amount of resources to continue to operate a data center, not mentioning the initial cost of putting one up. The marginilized communities that it affects directy are silenced, which seems to be a trope that most governments in all of history have enforced, and the end result is an enviornment that is ruined, countless communinties that are left without reliable running water, frequent energy blackouts, and also just a feeling of dispair that looms overhead due to this ever repeating pattern. But with continued fighting this can be overturned, as other topics have shown here.
</p>
